This paper is primarily focused on pedestrian detection, which is a subfield of computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the use of diverse and dense datasets for pre-training, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The study also involves evaluating the performance of different detectors, which can be considered as a machine learning problem (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the application of pedestrian detection in autonomous driving, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). Finally, the paper also discusses the limitations of existing detectors and the need for better evaluation methods, which can be considered as a critique of existing research (cs.CR).
